<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Diaphoneme&action=edit&section=1.php.html" title="Edit section: Usage">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Usage">Usage</span></h2>
<p>The term <i>diaphone</i> first appeared in usage by phoneticians like <a href="Daniel_Jones_(phonetician)" title="Daniel Jones (phonetician)">Daniel Jones</a><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> and <a href="../Harold_E._Palmer" title="Harold E. Palmer">Harold E. Palmer</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> Jones, who was more interested in transcription and coping with dialectal variation<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup> than with how <a href="#Cognitive_reality">cognitively real</a> the phenomenon is,<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> originally used <i>diaphone</i> to refer to the family of sounds that are realized differently depending on dialect but that speakers consider to be the same;<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup> an individual dialect or speaker's realization of this diaphone was called a <i>diaphonic variant</i>. Because of confusion related to usage, Jones later coined the term <i>diaphoneme</i> to refer to his earlier sense of <i>diaphone</i> (the class of sounds) and used <i>diaphone</i> to refer to the variants.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10"><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>A diaphonemic inventory is a specific <a href="Diasystem" title="Diasystem">diasystem</a> (a term popularized by <a href="Uriel_Weinreich" title="Uriel Weinreich">Uriel Weinreich</a>) that superimposes dialectal contrasts to access all contrasts in all dialects that are included.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup> This consists of a shared core inventory<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12"><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup> and, when accounting for contrasts not made by all dialects (whether they are historical contrasts that have <a href="Phonological_change#Merger" title="Phonological change">been lost</a> or <a href="Phonological_change#Split" title="Phonological change">innovative ones</a> not made in all varieties <sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup>), only as many contrasts as are needed.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14"><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15"><span>[</span>15<span>]</span></a></sup> The diaphonemic approach gets away from the assumption that linguistic communities are homogeneous, allows multiple varieties to be described in the same terms (something important for situations where people have abilities in more than one variety),<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16"><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup> and helps in ascertaining where speakers make diaphonic identifications as a result of similarities and differences between the varieties involved.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17"><span>[</span>17<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The <b>linguistic variable</b>, a similar<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18"><span>[</span>18<span>]</span></a></sup> concept presented by <a href="William_Labov" title="William Labov">William Labov</a>, refers to features with variations that are referentially identical but carry social and stylistic meaning.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19"><span>[</span>19<span>]</span></a></sup> This could include phonological, as well as morphological and syntactic phenomena.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20"><span>[</span>20<span>]</span></a></sup> Labov also developed <a href="Variable_rules_analysis" title="Variable rules analysis">variable rules analysis</a>, with variable rules being those that all members of a speech community (presumably) possess but vary in the frequency of use.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21"><span>[</span>21<span>]</span></a></sup> The latter concept met resistance from scholars for a number of reasons<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22"><span>[</span>22<span>]</span></a></sup> including the argument from critics that knowledge of rule probabilities was too far from speakers' competence.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23"><span>[</span>23<span>]</span></a></sup> Because of these problems, use of variable rules analysis died down by the end of the 1980s.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24"><span>[</span>24<span>]</span></a></sup> Nevertheless, the linguistic variable is still used in <a href="Sociolinguistics" title="Sociolinguistics">sociolinguistics</a>. For Labov, grouping variants together was justified by their tendency to fluctuate between each other within the same set of words.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25"><span>[</span>25<span>]</span></a></sup> For example, Labov presented the variants of the vowel of <i>bad</i> or <i>dance</i>:</p>
<table class="wikitable" align="center">
<tr>
<th>Phonetic<br />
value</th>
